535-566 Let no one be surprised that the lava-stone is susible. Heraclitus tells us that fire is the seed of all things, and that everything gives way to fire. We see that it is so in our own experiments with the hardest metals, bronze, lead, iron, gold. True, the lava-stone does not succumb readily, with a small fire, or in open daylight3 you must have a close furnace, and a fire of more than average strength3 then it will fuse. And where can you find a furnace like Aetna; nurse of secret fire, only comparable with the fires launched by Jupiter ; this too seconded by a tense spirit which is forced out of the narrow pores of the mountain?
